 government of cambodia has made a strong political commitment in responses to the need for prevention of hiv transmission and care for people living with hiv aids under technical and financial supports from national and international agencies several prevention and intervention programs have been successfully implemented and the who unaids recognized that the cambodia's hiv aids epidemic appeared to be stabilized in 2002 the estimated hiv prevalence in adult general population declined to 0.5 in 2009 down from 1.2 in 2001 among women visiting antenatal care clinics the prevalence also declined from 2.1 in 1999 to 1.1 in 2006 there was also a gradual increase in the percentage of hiv infected pregnant women who received antiretroviral therapy to reduce the risk of mother to child transmission from 1.2 in 2003 to 11.2 in 2007 to 32.3 in 2009 despite the decline of hiv prevalence in general population the prevalence remains high among high risk groups such as commercial sex workers men who have sex with men and injecting drug users furthermore the so called prevention successful country is also seeing the growing needs for hiv aids treatment and care this seminar highlights the past and current features of cambodia's hiv aids epidemic lessons learned from prevention and care policies and future challenges that cambodia may face in the battles against hiv aids dr siyan yi joins the walter h shorenstein asia pacific research center shorenstein aparc during the 2011 12 academic year from the national center of global health and medicine and the university of tokyo japan where he jointly served as a research fellow and lecturer he has also served as an adjunct faculty member at cambodia's school of public health the national institute of public health and the school of international studies at the royal university of phnom penh location philippines conference room encina hall 616 serra st 3rd floor stanford university stanford ca 94305 directions map fsi contact lisa lee 